# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cleanup-hitter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:cleanup-hitter/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons was born in Milwaukee and grew up as a fan of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] In the fourth grade, he received a spanking from his father for insisting that he wanted to play professional baseball.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] When he persisted in asserting his desire to be a baseball player, his father replied that he had better become a good player.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons was known by his birth surname (Szymanski), until he was playing for a local minor league team and he was tired of hearing people mispronounce it.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He saw an advertisement for a company named Simmons Hardware and decided to take on the last name of Simmons.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] In 1925, his second season with Philadelphia, Simmons led the AL with 253 hits and 392 total bases, while posting a .387 batting average, 24 home runs and 129 runs batted in (RBI).
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He scored 122 runs, hit 43 doubles, and finished with a .599 slugging percentage.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons's 85 multi-hit games constitute a single-season MLB record.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He earned the second-most votes for the league's Most Valuable Player Award.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] In the following three seasons, he hit .341, .392 and .351 and drove in 110, 108 and 107 runs in those respective years, while finishing fifth in 1926 MVP voting and fourth in 1927.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons led the A's to the AL pennant in 1929, as Philadelphia went 104–46, finishing 18 games ahead of the New York Yankees.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] The A's went on to defeat the Chicago Cubs in five games to win the World Series.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] That season, he hit .365 with 34 home runs and led the AL with 157 RBI.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He also scored 114 runs, had 212 hits with 41 doubles and a .642 slugging percentage.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] In the 1929 World Series, Simmons batted .300 with two home runs, five RBIs and scored six runs.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons's best year as a player was in 1930, when he won his first of successive batting titles, hitting .381 with 36 home runs, 211 hits, 41 doubles and 16 triples.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He had a slugging percentage of .708, drove in 165 runs and scored 152 runs in 138 games.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] The A's won the AL pennant again, going 102–52, and defeated the St.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Louis Cardinals to win back-to-back World Series titles.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] In the 1930 World Series, Simmons batted .364 with two home runs and four RBI with a .727 slugging percentage.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] In 1931, the A's won their third straight AL pennant, by 13.5 games over the Yankees, going 107–45.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons won his second batting title, hitting .390 with 22 home runs, 128 RBI, 100 runs scored, 200 hits, 37 doubles, 13 triples and a .641 slugging percentage while playing in only 128 games.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He finished third in AL MVP voting behind his MVP teammate Lefty Grove and the Yankees' Lou Gehrig.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] The A's were upset in their quest for a third consecutive World Series title, losing the 1931 World Series in seven games to the Cardinals.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons hit .333 with two home runs and eight RBI in the series.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] In a final season with Philadelphia, Simmons led the AL with 216 hits.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He batted .322, with 35 home runs, 151 RBIs and 144 runs scored in 1932.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons finished his Athletics tenure with a .356 batting average, 209 home runs, 1,179 RBI and 969 runs scored in 1,290 games.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He drove in 100+ runs in all nine seasons and scored 100 or more runs in five seasons.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] In three World Series appearances for the A's, Simmons hit .333 with six home runs, 17 RBI and 15 runs scored in 18 games.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] In late September 1932, the Athletics sold Simmons, Mule Haas and Jimmy Dykes to the Chicago White Sox for cash.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] The amount of the purchase was not disclosed at the time the sale was reported, though it was said to be the largest cash purchase ever made by the White Sox and possibly the largest purchase in AL history.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Newspaper reports speculated that Athletics owner Connie Mack might be breaking apart the Athletics team that had been so successful between 1929 and 1931.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] During his first season in Chicago, Simmons batted .331 with 14 home runs, 119 RBI and 200 hits.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] In 1934, he batted .344 with 18 home runs, 104 RBI, 102 runs scored and 192 hits in 138 games.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] After a disappointing final season with the White Sox, which saw Simmons bat just.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] 267 with 16 home runs and 79 RBI in 128 games (the first time in his 11-year career he did not reach .300 and 100+ RBI), he rebounded by hitting .327 with 13 home runs, 112 RBI and 96 runs scored in 1936 for the Detroit Tigers.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] In 1937, he struggled again, this time with the Washington Senators, batting just .279 with 8 home runs and 84 RBIs in 103 games.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He rebounded with a stellar season in 1938, batting .302 with 21 home runs and 95 RBI in just 125 games for Washington.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] His 21 home runs that year gave Simmons the distinction of being the first player to hit 20 home runs in a year for the Senators.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons was purchased from the Senators by the Boston Bees in December 1938.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] The purchase price was not immediately revealed, though Simmons was reported as not getting along with Senators owner Clark Griffith.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons was purchased from the Bees by the Cincinnati Reds on August 31, 1939.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] The Reds won the NL pennant that year, and Simmons got to play in his final World Series.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He played in one game in the 1939 World Series, going one for four with a double and a run scored.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons played in the major leagues until 1944, when he finished his career with his original team, the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons was one of the best hitters in MLB history.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He had a career batting average of .334.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He hit .340 or better in eight different seasons, with four seasons of better than .380.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He recorded a .300 batting average and 100 or more RBI in his first 11 major league seasons.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons accumulated 1,500 hits in 1,040 games and 2,000 hits in 1,393 games, numbers that remain the fewest games needed to attain both marks in major league history.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He compiled 200 hits or better in a season six times, with five of those being consecutive (1929–33), and had 199 and 192 hits in 1926 and 1934.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He compiled more hits than any right-handed batter in AL history until surpassed by Al Kaline.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons recorded 8 five-hit games and 52 four-hit games in the majors.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons hit 307 career home runs, finishing in the top six in AL in home runs for seven consecutive seasons (1925–32).
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] In 19 World Series games, he hit .329 with 6 home runs, 17 RBI, 15 runs scored and a .658 slugging percentage.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He was also a fine outfielder in his era, recording a career .982 fielding percentage.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He recorded exactly 5,000 putouts in his MLB career.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons was nicknamed "Bucketfoot Al" because he strode toward third base when hitting, hence hitting "with his foot in the bucket", an old baseball term.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] After his playing days ended, Simmons served as a coach for Mack's Athletics (1945–49) and the Cleveland Indians (1950).
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] In early April 1951, Simmons announced he was dealing with an undisclosed illness and would be stepping down as a coach of the Indians.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] While Cleveland manager Al López encouraged Simmons to think about his decision, Simmons said he could no longer help the team.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He had collapsed on a sidewalk near the Milwaukee Athletic Club, where he lived, and was thought to have suffered a heart attack.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] He was pronounced dead at a hospital a short time later.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] Simmons was elected to the Wisconsin Athletic Hall of Fame in 1951, the National Baseball Hall of Fame in 1953, and the National Polish-American Sports Hall of Fame in 1975.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] In 1999, Simmons ranked number 43 on *The Sporting News*' list of the 100 Greatest Baseball Players, and was a nominee for the Major League Baseball All-Century Team.
[src:cleanup-hitter/al-simmons] In the 2001 book *The New Bill James Historical Baseball Abstract*, Bill James ranked Simmons as the 71st greatest baseball player of all time and the seventh greatest MLB left fielder of all time.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Belle was a five-time All-Star and Silver Slugger.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He retired with a .295 career batting average, and averaged 37 home runs and 120 runs batted in (RBIs) per season between 1991 and 2000.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He is one of only 10 players in MLB history to have nine consecutive 100-RBI seasons.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Albert and his fraternal twin, Terry, were born on August 25, 1966, in Shreveport, Louisiana, the son of Albert Belle Sr., a high school baseball and football coach, and Carrie Belle, a former math teacher.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He attained the rank of Eagle Scout in the Boy Scouts of America.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Belle attended Huntington High School in Shreveport, where he was a star baseball and football player, a member of the National Honor Society, and vice president of the local Future Business Leaders of America.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He graduated sixth in his high school class and made the all-state baseball team twice.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In 1984, he was selected to play for the US in the Junior Olympics, in which the U.S. won a silver medal.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He played outfield and pitched, winning one game.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] After graduation, Belle accepted a baseball scholarship to Louisiana State University.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Belle played college baseball at Louisiana State University from 1985 to 1987, where he made first-team All-SEC in 1986 and 1987 and played in 184 games, with 585 at bats, 194 hits, 30 doubles, 49 home runs, 172 RBIs, 157 runs, a .670 slugging percentage, and a .332 batting average.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In 1986, he played collegiate summer baseball in the Cape Cod Baseball League for the Chatham A's and was named a league all-star, then returned to the league in 1987 to play for the Hyannis Mets.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In his junior year, he was batting .349 before an incident involving a heckler insulting him with racial epithets at an SEC Tournament game led to a suspension that kept him out of the College World Series.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] After college, Belle was drafted by the Cleveland Indians in the second round (47th overall) of the 1987 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Belle made his major league debut on July 15, 1989, going 1-for-4 with one RBI in a 7–1 win against the Texas Rangers.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He recorded an RBI single off Rangers pitcher Nolan Ryan in his first career at bat.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] On July 19, Belle hit his first major league home run and went 2-for-4, helping Cleveland to a 10–1 victory over the Minnesota Twins.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He ultimately played in 62 games during his first season, batting .225 with seven home runs and 37 RBIs.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Belle became the fourth player to have eight straight seasons of 30 home runs and 100 RBIs, joining Babe Ruth, Jimmie Foxx, and Lou Gehrig (a feat since matched by Albert Pujols, Rafael Palmeiro, Manny Ramirez, and Alex Rodriguez).
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He was an accomplished baserunner, with a career-high 23 steals in 1993, and 17 steals in 1999 despite hip problems that plagued him late in his career.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He led the league three times in RBIs, three times in total bases, three times in extra-base hits, and twice in slugging.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He was a five-time All-Star between 1993 and 1997.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He had a strong throwing arm and was a gifted pitcher in high school.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] His range factor by games played was consistently higher than the major league average at that position; nevertheless, he still managed to accrue a -63 "total zone runs" during 12 major league seasons.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Belle's career highs in home runs, RBIs, batting average, runs scored, and walks occurred in five separate seasons.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In 2006, the *Hardball Times* published a statistical comparison of Belle's career statistics with those of 60 of his current and former peers.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] The article ranked him in career "prime value", behind Hall of Famers Ralph Kiner and Frank Thomas.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In 1994, Belle lost the batting title to New York Yankees outfielder Paul O'Neill, .359 to .357.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In 1995, Belle became the first player in MLB history to hit 50 home runs and 50 doubles in the same season; the last player before him to reach as many as 40 in both categories had been Willie Stargell in 1973.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] The achievement was more impressive because Belle played only 143 games in 1995 due to a season shortened by the previous year's player strike.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Belle's surly reputation and disdain of the media cost him votes for the 1995 MVP Award.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] This was in the middle of a three-year streak in which Belle finished third, second, and third for the American League MVP.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Belle had two other top-10 MVP finishes, in 1993 (seventh) and 1998 (eighth).
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] On November 19, 1996, Belle signed a five-year, $55 million (equivalent to $110 million today) deal with the Chicago White Sox as a free agent.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] This contract made him the highest-paid player in baseball for a brief period and the first player in baseball history to make $10 million in a season.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He enjoyed two great seasons in Chicago, including a career-high 27-game hitting streak in May 1997, and came close to another 50/50 season in 1998 with 49 home runs (a White Sox team record that still stands) and 48 doubles.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He also drove in 152 runs to break Zeke Bonura's single-season franchise record of 138 in 1936 (to date, the RBI total also remains a White Sox single-season record).
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Additionally, when Cal Ripken Jr. ended his record consecutive game streak at 2,632 in September 1998, Belle took over as MLB's active leader in the category (his streak of 392 consecutive games ended the next year due to a perceived lack of hustle viewed by his manager).
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Belle's contract with the White Sox had an unusual clause allowing him to demand that he would remain one of the three highest-paid players in baseball.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In October 1998, he invoked the clause, and when the White Sox declined to give him a raise, he immediately became a free agent.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He again became the game's highest-paid player, signing a five-year, $65 million ($126 million today) deal with the Baltimore Orioles on December 1, 1998.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] His career ended just two seasons later, though, when he was forced into retirement at age 34 by degenerative hip osteoarthritis.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He was kept on Baltimore's active 40-man roster for the next three years as a condition of the insurance policy that largely reimbursed the Orioles for the remainder of his contract.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Belle homered in the final at-bat of his MLB career at Oriole Park at Camden Yards on October 1, 2000.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In 1,539 games over 12 seasons, Belle posted a .295 batting average (1,726-for-5,853) with 974 runs, 389 doubles, 21 triples, 381 home runs, 1,239 RBIs, 88 stolen bases, 683 bases on balls, .369 on-base percentage, and .564 slugging percentage.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Defensively, he recorded a .976 fielding percentage playing at left and right field.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In 18 postseason games, he hit .230 (14-for-61) with 10 runs, two doubles, six home runs, 14 RBIs, one stolen base, and 14 walks.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In 1990, the Indians sent Belle to the Cleveland Clinic for two months for alcoholism rehabilitation.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Belle was suspended in 1994 for using a corked bat, resulting in a seven-game suspension.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] The incident gained further notoriety when teammate Jason Grimsley crawled through the building's ceiling panels to break into the locked umpires' dressing room, where he replaced Belle's corked bat with a teammate's bat.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Belle was fined in 1996 for knocking down Brewers infielder Fernando Viña, who had blocked his way between bases.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] A profane outburst directed at a group of reporters in his team's dugout was widely reported during the 1995 World Series.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He was unrepentant afterward: "The Indians wanted me to issue a statement of regret when the fine was announced, but I told them to take it out.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] I apologize for nothing." Eventually, Belle routinely refused to speak with the media whatsoever, explaining that players like Steve Carlton also did not interview and that he preferred to concentrate on baseball.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] It was taken as fact in baseball circles that Albert Belle was nuts....
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He slurped coffee constantly and seemed to be in a perpetual caffeinated frenzy.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Belle preferred to have the clubhouse cold, below 60°F, and when one chilly teammate turned up the heat, Belle walked over, turned down the thermostat, and smashed it with his bat.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] The Indians billed him $10,000 a year for the damage he caused in clubhouses on the road and at home, and tolerated his behavior only because he was an awesome slugger....
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Sorry, there'll be no words of sympathy here for Albert Belle.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] He was a surly jerk before he got hurt and now he's a hurt surly jerk....He was no credit to the game.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In his first year of Hall of Fame eligibility (2006), he garnered only 7.7% of the baseball writers' votes, missing election by an extremely wide margin.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] His vote total, though, was high enough to keep his name on the ballot for the following year.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In 2007, he received only 19 votes (3.5%), knocking him off the ballot.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In retirement, Belle had his first encounter with the Cleveland Indians since leaving the club in 1996, during their 2012 spring training in Goodyear, Arizona, and was joined by former teammates Kenny Lofton, Sandy Alomar Jr., and Carlos Baerga.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In spite of this, Belle declined both to attend the 20th-anniversary celebration of the 1995 World Series team in 2015 and the 2016 ceremony when he was inducted into the Indians team Hall of Fame.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In October 1995, Belle's house in Euclid, Ohio, was egged by teenagers after he turned away trick-or-treaters on Halloween.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Belle chased one of the trick-or-treaters in his car.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] Belle was fined $100 for reckless operation of a vehicle.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] The guardian of the teenager later sued Belle for $850,000, contending that Belle's car had bumped into the teenager.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] In 2006, Belle was sentenced to 90 days in jail and five years' probation after he admitted to stalking his former girlfriend.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] On March 25, 2018, Belle was arrested in Scottsdale, Arizona, and charged with indecent exposure and driving under the influence.
[src:cleanup-hitter/albert-belle] All charges were dismissed the following month.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] The **American League of Professional Baseball Clubs**, known simply as the **American League** (**AL**), is the younger of two leagues constituting Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] It developed from the Western League, a minor league based in the Great Lakes states, which eventually aspired to major league status.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] It is sometimes called the **Junior Circuit** because it claimed Major League status for the 1901 season, 25 years after the formation of the National League (the "Senior Circuit").
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Since 1903, the American League champion has played in the World Series against the National League champion with only two exceptions: 1904, when the NL champion New York Giants refused to play their AL counterpart, and 1994, when a players' strike resulted in the cancellation of the Series.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Through 2025, American League teams have won 68 of the 121 World Series played since 1903.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] The New York Yankees have won 27 World Series and 41 American League titles, the most in major league history.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] The Philadelphia/Kansas City/Oakland Athletics have won the second most AL titles with 15, followed by the Boston Red Sox with 14.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] For decades, Major League baseball clubs only played teams from their own league during the regular season and playoffs, with only the two pennant winners meeting in the World Series.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] The AL and NL also employed and trained their own umpires, who only worked regular season games in their own league.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] These differences resulted in the leagues developing slightly different strategies and styles of play.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] The American League was usually regarded as the less "traditional" league during the 20th century, a reputation most exemplified by the introduction of the designated hitter rule in 1973, which encouraged AL managers to largely abandon "smallball" tactics.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Though both leagues agreed to be jointly governed by a commissioner in 1920, they remained separate business entities with their own presidents and management.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] This was the case until after the 1999 season, when the American League legally merged with the National League under the auspices of Major League Baseball, which now operates much like other North American professional sports leagues, albeit with two "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Originally a minor league known as the Western League, which existed from 1885 to 1899 with teams in mostly Great Lakes states, the league changed its name to the American League for the 1900 season and the next year developed into a second major league as a competitor to the older National League.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] This was prompted by the NL dropping four teams following the 1899 season after having absorbed its previous rival, the American Association, which disbanded in 1891 after ten seasons.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] In its early history of the late 1880s, the minor Western League struggled until 1894, when Ban Johnson became the president of the league.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Johnson pushed the league to rise to major league status, after the name change to the American League was decided in a league meeting in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, at the former Republican Hotel.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] A historical marker is at the intersection of North Dr.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Drive and West Kilbourn Avenue where the hotel once stood.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] In March 1904, Johnson moved the league's headquarters from Chicago to New York.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Babe Ruth, noted as one of the most prolific hitters in Major League Baseball history, spent the majority of his career in the American League with the Boston Red Sox and the New York Yankees.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] From 1973 to 2022 The American League had one notable difference versus the rival National League, as it had the designated hitter rule.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Under the rule, a team may use a batter in its lineup who is not in the field defensively, replacing the pitcher in the batting order, compared to the old rule that made it mandatory for the pitcher to bat.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] In the last two decades, the season schedule has allowed occasional interleague play.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] In 1969, the AL (and NL) were divided into East and West divisions, with a postseason playoff series for the pennant and the right to play in the World Series.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Until the late 1970s, league umpires working behind home plate wore large, balloon-style chest protectors worn outside the shirt or coat, while their colleagues in the National League wore chest protectors inside the shirt or coat.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] In 1977, new umpires (including Steve Palermo) had to wear the inside chest protector, although those on staff wearing the outside protector could continue to do so.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Most umpires made the switch to the inside protector, led by Don Denkinger in 1975 and Jim Evans the next year, although several did not, including Bill Haller, Russ Goetz, George Maloney, Bill Kunkel and Jerry Neudecker, who became the last full-time MLB umpire to use the outside protector in 1985.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] In 1998, the newly franchised Tampa Bay Devil Rays joined the league, and the Arizona Diamondbacks joined the National League: i.e., each league added a fifteenth team.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] An odd number of teams per league meant that at least one team in each league would have to be idle on any given day, or alternatively, that odd team out would have had to play an interleague game against its counterpart in the other league.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] The initial plan was to have three five-team divisions per league with inter-league play year-round—possibly as many as 30 interleague games per team each year.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] For various reasons, it soon seemed more practical to have an even number of teams in both leagues.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed to change leagues to become the National League's 16th team, moving from the AL Central to the NL Central.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers were moved from the AL East to the AL Central, making room for the Devil Rays in the East.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Even after expansion, the American League then continued with 14 teams.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] This situation changed again in 2013 when the Houston Astros moved from the National League Central division to the American League West.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] The Astros had been in the NL for 51 years since beginning as an expansion team in 1962.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Since their move, both leagues now consist of 15 teams.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] For the first 96 years, American League teams faced their National League counterparts only in exhibition games or in the World Series.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Beginning in 1997, interleague games have been played during the regular season and count in the standings.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] As part of the agreement instituting interleague play, the designated-hitter rule was used only in games where the American League team is the home team, until the 2022 season, when the universal DH rule was implemented.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] In 2023, American League teams played 46 regular season interleague games against all 15 National League teams, 23 at home and 23 on the road.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] In 2000, the American League ended its status as a legally independent entity when the American and National Leagues were both merged into the legal entity Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] This left MLB as a single league, divided into two parts, also called leagues.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] This change in legal status had no effect on play, scheduling, and so forth.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] There were eight charter teams in 1901, the league's first year as a major league, and the next year the original Milwaukee Brewers (not to be confused with the current Milwaukee Brewers) moved to St.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Louis Browns, and the year after the New York Highlanders replaced the disbanded original Baltimore Orioles.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Those eight franchises constituted the league for 52 seasons until the Browns moved to Baltimore and took up the Orioles name.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] The first line is the transformation of the American League (AL) to a major league in 1901.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] The second line is the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] The third line marks the legal merger of the American and National Leagues into a single Major League Baseball in 2000.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] World Series championships are shown with a "•", American League Pennants before the World Series are shown with a "#", and American League Pennants who lost the World Series are shown with a "^".
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] No World Series was played in 1904, so the pennant winners for each league are indicated.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike, there were no pennant or World Series winners in 1994, so this year is left blank.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] Following the 1999 season, the American and National Leagues were merged with Major League Baseball, and the leagues ceased to exist as business entities.
[src:cleanup-hitter/american-league] The position of the American League President and National League President became honorary.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] In baseball, an **appeal play** occurs when a member of the defensive team calls the attention of an umpire to an infraction that they would otherwise ignore.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] To properly execute a live ball appeal, a fielder must, with a live ball, tag the runner or base in question and communicate to the umpire what the infraction was and which runner committed the infraction.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] Such communication may be non-verbal, implicit, or assumed—so long as the intent of the fielder is clear to the umpire.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] Contrary to popular belief, an appeal out is not a force out unless it is regarding a missed force base.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] For example, if a runner from third base tags up and scores, but a runner from second base leaves too early, failing to tag up, and then is put out on the appeal, the run counts if it was scored before the appeal by the fielders.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] Rare situations with a viable appeal on a runner who misses his force base require the umpire to recognize an apparent fourth out.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] Umpires will only rule on legal appeals.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] A potential appeal is *viable* if the appeal is legal and the umpire knows that the runner has indeed committed an infraction and will be called out if the appeal is executed by a fielder.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] Suppose that runners are on first and third base, and the batter hits a fly ball.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] The runner on third tags up, leaving third base immediately after the outfielder touches the ball.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] The runner seems to score, beating the throw home, but failing to touch home plate.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] The runner proceeds into his dugout without again attempting to touch home base.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] The runner on first base stays at first base, and action becomes relaxed while the ball is in the infield.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] The fielders now suspect that the runner left third base too early and also missed the plate.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] Suppose then that a fielder, with the live ball, touches home base and says to the nearest umpire, "I think they never touched home." This is a legal and viable appeal, and so the umpire should call the runner out and direct that his run shall not count.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] Since the ball was live (and indeed must be for appeals to be legal), the runner from first could have attempted to advance at any time during the appeals.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] If the defense attempts to play on that runner, their opportunity to appeal the runner from third base is lost, and the run would count regardless of any subsequent attempt to appeal.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] A member of the defensive team may appeal to the umpire when a batter bats out of turn.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] The umpire then enforces the penalty for batting out of turn, if any.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] The ball must be live for this as for any appeal.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] After the appeal is made, the umpire will usually signal "Time" and figure out whether the appeal is successful.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] The field umpire then signals whether the batter swung, and such a judgment must, by rule, prevail.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] The umpire asked is usually the first-base umpire (or third-base, if the batter is left-handed).
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] The plate umpire is not required to ask for assistance if they believe the request is making a farce of the game.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] If the bat barely left the shoulder of the batter and the catcher appeals the "no-swing" call, the umpire will probably deny the appeal.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] This procedure was introduced because it is commonplace for a plate umpire to be unable to see some swings.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] A manager may ask an umpire to request assistance on other plays where another umpire had a better view, but the umpire is not required to do so.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] Such requests are common when a close home run or foul ball call is disputed, or when determining the accuracy of a close catch or no catch call.
[src:cleanup-hitter/appeal-play] In such a case, the plate umpire would put a new ball in play, and after the ball became live by rule, the defense could appeal the missed base.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] In baseball, an **assist** (denoted by **A**) is a defensive statistic, baseball being one of the few sports in which the *defensive* team controls the ball.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] An assist is credited to every defensive player who fields or touches the ball (after it has been hit by the batter) prior to the recording of a putout, even if the contact was unintentional.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] For example, if a ball strikes a player's leg and bounces off him to another fielder, who tags the baserunner, the first player is credited with an assist.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] A fielder can receive a maximum of one assist per out recorded.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] An assist is also credited if a putout would have occurred, had another fielder not committed an error.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] For example, a shortstop might field a ground ball cleanly, but the first baseman might drop his throw.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] In this case, an error would be charged to the first baseman, and the shortstop would be credited with an assist.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] If a pitcher records a strikeout where the third strike is caught by the catcher, the pitcher is not credited with an assist.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] However, if the batter becomes a baserunner on a dropped third strike and the pitcher is involved in recording a putout by fielding the ball and either tagging the runner out or throwing to first base for the out, the pitcher is credited with an assist just as any other fielder would be.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] Assists are an important statistic for outfielders, as a play often occurs when a baserunner on the opposing team attempts to advance on the basepaths when the ball is hit to the outfield (even on a caught fly ball that results in an out; see tag up).
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] It is the outfielder's job to field the ball and make an accurate throw to another fielder who is covering the base before the runner reaches it.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] The fielder then attempts to tag the runner out.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] This is especially important if the runner was trying to reach home plate, as the assist and tag prevent the baserunner from scoring a run.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] Assists are much rarer for outfielders than infielders (with the exception of first basemen) because the play is harder to make, and also because outfielder assist situations occur less often than the traditional ground-ball assist for a shortstop, second baseman, or third baseman.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] However, as a result, outfield assists are worth far more than infield assists, and tell more about an outfielder's throwing arm than infielder assists do.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] In recent years, some sabermetricians have begun referring to assists by outfielders as **baserunner kills**.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] Some sabermetricians are also using *baserunner holds* as a statistic to measure outfield arms.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] A baserunner hold occurs when the baserunner does not attempt to advance an extra base on an outfielder out of concern of being thrown out by a strong, accurate throw.
[src:cleanup-hitter/assist-baseball] This can be combined with baserunner kills for better accuracy, as runners often do not try for an extra base when an outfielder with an excellent arm is playing.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] In baseball, an **at bat** (**AB**) or **time at bat** is a batter's turn batting against a pitcher.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] An at bat is different from a plate appearance.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] A batter is credited with a plate appearance regardless of what happens upon completion of his turn at bat, but a batter is charged with an at bat only if that plate appearance does not have one of the results enumerated below.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] While at bats are used to calculate certain statistics, including batting average and slugging percentage, players can qualify for the season-ending rankings in these categories only if they accumulate 502 plate appearances during the season.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] In addition, if the inning ends during an at bat (due to the third out being made by a runner caught stealing, for example), no at bat or plate appearance will result because neither were completed.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] An at bat is a specific type of plate appearance in which the batter stands at the plate intending to put the ball in play and get on base.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] This is why at bats, and not plate appearances, are used to calculate batting average, as plate appearances in general can result in many outcomes that do not necessarily involve putting the ball in play, and batting average specifically measures a batter's contact hitting.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] Pete Rose had 14,053 career at bats, the all-time major league and National League record.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] The American League record is held by Carl Yastrzemski, whose 11,988 career at bats were all in the AL.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] The single season record is held by Jimmy Rollins, who had 716 at bats in 2007.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] Willie Wilson, Ichiro Suzuki and Juan Samuel also had more than 700 at bats in a season.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] 14 players share the single game record of 11 at bats in a single game, all of which were extra inning games.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] In games of 9 innings or fewer, the record is 7 at bats and has occurred more than 200 times.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] The team record for most at bats in a single season is 5,781 by the 1997 Boston Red Sox.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] "At bat", "up", "up at bat", and "at the plate" are all phrases describing a batter who is facing the pitcher.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] Just because a player is described as being "at bat" in this sense, he will not necessarily be given an at bat in his statistics; the phrase actually signifies a plate appearance (assuming it is eventually completed).
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] This ambiguous terminology is usually clarified by context.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] To refer explicitly to a statistical "at bat", the term "official at bat" is sometimes used.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] Official Baseball Rule 5.06(c) provides that "[a] batter has legally completed his *time at bat* when he is put out or becomes a runner" (emphasis added).
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] The "time at bat" defined in this rule is more commonly referred to as a plate appearance, and the playing rules (Rules 1 through 8) uses the phrase "time at bat" in this sense.
[src:cleanup-hitter/at-bat] In contrast, the scoring rules use the phrase "time at bat" to refer to the statistic **at bat**, defined in Rule 9.02(a)(1), but sometimes uses the phrase "official time at bat" or refers back to Rule 9.02(a)(1) when mentioning the statistic.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] In baseball, a **cleanup hitter** is the fourth hitter in the batting order.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] The cleanup hitter is traditionally the team's most powerful hitter.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] His job is to "clean up the bases", that is, drive in base runners.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] The thinking behind the use of the cleanup hitter is that at least one of the batters before him will reach base somehow, usually via a walk or a base hit.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] Traditionally, the lead off hitter, the number one spot in the batting order, has good foot speed, plate discipline, and a high on-base percentage.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] The second batter is usually a contact hitter, meaning he is able to consistently make contact with the ball and put it in play to move base runners forward and into scoring position.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] The first or second batter might bunt his way on base as they both will be speedy runners.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] The third batter is usually the best batter, the hitter with the highest batting average.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] He has the role of scoring runs himself, but his job comes down to getting on base for the cleanup hitter to have a turn to bat in the same inning.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] The cleanup hitter coming up to hit—if he has runners on base—has the opportunity to produce runs by getting a base hit or a home run.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] The third and fourth batters tend to be interchangeable in the batting order.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] The fifth batter in the lineup also has the job of batting in runs, in effect a backup for the cleanup hitter.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] He shares multiple traits with the cleanup hitter and therefore can compete for the cleanup hitter's spot in the batting order.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] Batters six to nine typically descend in batting skill level, meaning that the ninth batter is often the least effective batter in the lineup.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] Each individual hitter's strengths and weaknesses determine their spot on the daily lineup card.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] A manager may also take into account a batters tendency to hit in clutch situations or focus on home run ability.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] Since the home run is by far the most sure-fire method of batting in baserunners, the annual Home Run Derby tends to be a who's who of cleanup hitters from around the league.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] That being said, a hitter with an unspectacular home run rate who is instead reliable when it comes to extra-base hits can also be a valuable tool for scoring with runners in scoring position (RISP).
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] It is ultimately a question of how well a player fits into the rest of the lineup which determines the run-scoring potential of the cleanup spot.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] The designated hitter (DH) is a batter that hits for the pitcher and never plays defense.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] The DH is important because the DH is usually one of the better hitters.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] It is a trend that the DH is either in the third, fourth, or fifth spot in the lineup.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] The DH was adopted by the American League of North American Major League Baseball in 1973 and by the National League in 2022.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] In games without a DH, the pitcher hit in the lineup unless another player pinch hit for the pitcher, in which case the pitcher left the game and was replaced for the team's next defensive half-inning.
[src:cleanup-hitter/cleanup-hitter] Between 1973 and 2022, when there were interleague games and the National League was the home team, the American League team did not use a DH, and their pitchers took their turn at bat.
